VALUES
  (
    'bb020005-6005-4005-a005-bbbbbbbb0005',
    'bb010001-5001-4001-9001-bbbbbbbb0001',
    'en',
    'What is Carbon Fiber? Properties and Applications',
    'what-is-carbon-fiber',
    JSON_OBJECT('html', '<p>Carbon fiber is an advanced reinforcement material made of extremely thin filaments, roughly 5-10 microns in diameter, composed mostly of carbon atoms. When these filaments are combined with a resin system (typically epoxy), the result is a composite known in engineering as CFRP (Carbon Fiber Reinforced Polymer). The defining advantage of carbon fiber is its ability to deliver high strength at very low weight, offering a far more efficient strength-to-weight ratio than metals.</p> <p>This guide covers the core properties of carbon fiber, how it is manufactured, the industries that rely on it, and the engineering decisions required to achieve the right result.</p> <h2>Key Properties of Carbon Fiber</h2> <p>The technical edge of carbon fiber comes not from a single trait but from a combination of them:</p> <ul> <li><strong>High strength-to-weight ratio:</strong> Achieves the same strength with a much lighter structure.</li> <li><strong>High stiffness:</strong> With proper laminate design it deflects minimally under load.</li> <li><strong>Dimensional stability:</strong> A low thermal expansion coefficient keeps its shape across temperature changes.</li> <li><strong>Corrosion resistance:</strong> Unlike metals it does not rust and withstands humid, chemical environments.</li> <li><strong>Fatigue resistance:</strong> Provides a long service life under repeated loads.</li> </ul> <h2>Comparison with Steel and Aluminum</h2> <p>Comparing carbon fiber with common engineering materials makes its advantage concrete:</p> <table> <thead><tr><th>Property</th><th>Carbon Fiber (CFRP)</th><th>Steel</th><th>Aluminum</th></tr></thead> <tbody> <tr><td>Density (g/cm³)</td><td>1.5 - 1.6</td><td>7.8</td><td>2.7</td></tr> <tr><td>Specific strength</td><td>Very high</td><td>Medium</td><td>Medium</td></tr> <tr><td>Corrosion resistance</td><td>Excellent</td><td>Poor</td><td>Good</td></tr> <tr><td>Design flexibility</td><td>High</td><td>Limited</td><td>Medium</td></tr> </tbody> </table> <h2>How is Carbon Fiber Produced?</h2> <p>Carbon fiber is usually produced by subjecting PAN (polyacrylonitrile) based precursor fibers to controlled thermal processes. The process broadly includes the following stages:</p> <ol> <li><strong>Stabilization:</strong> Precursor fibers are heated to 200-300 °C in an oxygen environment to make the structure stable.</li> <li><strong>Carbonization:</strong> At high temperature in an oxygen-free environment, non-carbon atoms are removed and the carbon chain densifies.</li> <li><strong>Surface treatment and sizing:</strong> The fiber surface is prepared to improve adhesion to the resin.</li> <li><strong>Weaving or unidirectional layup:</strong> Fibers are turned into fabric, tape or unidirectional plies.</li> </ol> <h2>Application Areas</h2> <p>Carbon fiber stands out wherever strength and low weight are simultaneously critical. In aerospace and defense it is used for fuselage panels and structural components, in automotive for performance parts and lightweighting, in sports equipment for bicycle frames and rackets, and in industry for robot arms, custom machine components and protective enclosures. In the energy sector, large structures such as wind turbine blades also benefit from composite technology.</p> <h2>An Engineering Approach for the Right Result</h2> <p>Material selection alone is not enough to obtain the expected performance from carbon fiber. The resin system, number and orientation of layers, surface quality expectations and the production process must all be evaluated together. A poor laminate design can produce a weak part even with the right material. For this reason the project, the material and the geometry must be addressed together.</p> <h2>Types and Grades of Carbon Fiber</h2> <p>Carbon fiber is not a single material but a family with different mechanical properties. By modulus it is classified as standard modulus, intermediate modulus and high modulus; high-modulus fibers are stiffer, while standard-modulus fibers generally behave tougher. Fibers are also named by tow size, such as 3K, 6K and 12K, where the number expresses the count of filaments in a tow in thousands. The weave form matters too: unidirectional plies carry load most efficiently along a single axis, while woven fabrics provide multi-axis strength and easier draping. The right grade is chosen according to the working direction of the part and the expected stiffness.</p> <h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2> <p>Does carbon fiber rust? No; carbon fiber itself does not corrode, but galvanic-corrosion isolation must be applied at metal connection points. Is carbon fiber brittle? A properly designed laminate can show high impact resistance; brittleness is often the result of poor laminate design rather than the nature of the material. Is it suitable for every application? Because of its cost, glass-fiber reinforced alternatives may be more economical where weight and stiffness are not critical. For this reason the material decision should always be made by evaluating technical requirements and budget together.</p> <p>MOE Kompozit manages engineering support, sample validation and the transition to series production together, according to project needs. This ensures the theoretical advantage of the material is consistently reflected in the real part on the field.</p>'),
    'A comprehensive technical guide to what carbon fiber is, its key properties, how it is produced, its advantages, and its industrial applications from aerospace to automotive.',
    'What is Carbon Fiber? Properties and Uses',
    'Carbon fiber properties, production process, advantages and industrial applications, with a technical comparison against steel and aluminum.',
    'carbon fiber, composite material, carbon fiber properties, CFRP'
  ),
  (
    'bb020006-6006-4006-a006-bbbbbbbb0006',
    'bb010002-5002-4002-9002-bbbbbbbb0002',
    'en',
    'Differences Between FRP and Fiberglass',
    'frp-fiberglass-differences',
    JSON_OBJECT('html', '<p>FRP (Fiber Reinforced Polymer) and fiberglass are often used interchangeably in everyday language, yet technically they do not mean exactly the same thing. Fiberglass is the broad, general name for glass-fiber reinforced structures. FRP describes a polymer composite reinforced with fibers, where glass fiber is the most common reinforcement. Understanding this distinction is critical to selecting the right material for a project.</p> <p>In this article we clarify the FRP and fiberglass concepts, the differences between them, and which one to prefer in which situation.</p> <h2>What is FRP?</h2> <p>FRP is a composite material in which a polymer resin is reinforced with fibers, most commonly glass. Thanks to its mechanical strength, chemical resistance and favorable cost/performance balance, it is widely used in industrial bodies, covers, panels, tanks and protective parts. The flexibility of the production methods makes it suitable for everything from small custom parts to series production.</p> <h2>What Does Fiberglass Mean?</h2> <p>Fiberglass is the general term for glass-fiber reinforced composites and can involve different resin systems (polyester, vinylester, epoxy). In other words, glass-reinforced FRP is a type of fiberglass, but the term fiberglass is broader. Therefore the resin type, production method and target performance must be clarified separately when making a technical decision.</p> <h2>Key Differences Table</h2> <table> <thead><tr><th>Criterion</th><th>FRP (Glass Reinforced)</th><th>General Fiberglass</th></tr></thead> <tbody> <tr><td>Resin</td><td>Polymer (polyester/vinylester/epoxy)</td><td>Varies by application</td></tr> <tr><td>Scope</td><td>Specific composite class</td><td>Broad, general term</td></tr> <tr><td>Cost</td><td>Economical to mid-range</td><td>Depends on resin</td></tr> <tr><td>Typical use</td><td>Tanks, panels, bodies, covers</td><td>Insulation, marine, automotive</td></tr> </tbody> </table> <h2>Production Methods</h2> <p>Glass-fiber reinforced parts can be produced by different methods, and the chosen method directly affects the quality and cost of the part:</p> <ul> <li><strong>Hand lay-up:</strong> Flexible and economical for low volumes and large parts.</li> <li><strong>Spray-up:</strong> Efficient for surfaces that need fast coverage.</li> <li><strong>RTM (resin transfer molding):</strong> Repeatable, for parts that need two smooth surfaces.</li> <li><strong>Pultrusion:</strong> A continuous process for constant cross-section profiles and rods.</li> </ul> <h2>How to Choose the Right Material</h2> <p>The right choice is made by evaluating factors such as the operating environment, chemical exposure, mechanical load, temperature and surface expectations together. For example, a vinylester-resin fiberglass structure may be suitable for a tank exposed to chemical attack, while an economical polyester FRP solution may be better for a standard cover. When deciding, the focus should be on technical requirements, not just naming.</p> <h2>Advantages and Disadvantages</h2> <p>Glass-fiber reinforced composites offer significant advantages over metals, such as light weight, corrosion resistance and ease of molding. Electrical insulation and low maintenance cost are also reasons for preference in many industrial applications. On the other hand, lower stiffness and temperature resistance compared to carbon fiber can be limiting in some high-performance applications. For this reason FRP and fiberglass provide the most sensible solution in projects where the strength/cost balance is prominent.</p> <h2>In Which Sectors Is It Used?</h2> <p>FRP and fiberglass structures are used across a very wide field, including water and chemical storage tanks, treatment equipment, marine hulls, automotive panels, construction reinforcement profiles and municipal equipment. The main reason for this prevalence is that the material does not corrode and can be easily adapted to different geometries. Especially in applications that expect a long life outdoors or in chemical environments, it lowers the total cost of ownership compared to metal alternatives.</p> <h2>Maintenance and Long Life</h2> <p>One of the biggest advantages of FRP and fiberglass products is their low maintenance requirement. Because they do not corrode, they do not need regular painting or rust protection like metal structures. Nevertheless, it should be remembered that the gelcoat layer on the surface can dull over time under UV exposure; although this does not affect structural strength, it can be addressed with periodic surface care. A properly produced FRP part can serve for decades under suitable conditions, and this long life more than compensates for the initial investment cost.</p> <p>MOE Kompozit analyzes the technical requirements of the project to recommend the right resin and production method, and runs the process together from the sample stage to series production.</p>'),
    'A comprehensive guide explaining what FRP and fiberglass actually mean, the differences between them, their production methods, and how to choose the right material.',
    'FRP vs Fiberglass: A Technical Comparison',
    'Technical differences between FRP and fiberglass, production methods, advantages and a practical guide to choosing the right composite material.',
    'FRP, fiberglass, glass fiber, composite comparison, GRP'
  ),
  (
    'bb020007-6007-4007-a007-bbbbbbbb0007',
    'bb010003-5003-4003-9003-bbbbbbbb0003',
    'en',
    'Quality Control Processes in Composite Materials',
    'composite-quality-control',
    JSON_OBJECT('html', '<p>Quality control in composite manufacturing is often thought of as merely final-product inspection; in reality, true quality is a holistic discipline that spans from raw-material intake to mold preparation, from process parameters to final inspection and documentation. Because strength in composites is largely formed during production, the goal is not to detect a defect afterwards but to prevent it from occurring.</p> <p>In this article we cover the main stages of composite quality control, the testing methods used, and how to guarantee repeatability in series production.</p> <h2>Main Control Stages</h2> <p>An effective quality-control chain covers every stage of the part lifecycle:</p> <ol> <li><strong>Raw material and reinforcement control:</strong> The properties and shelf life of resin, hardener and fiber are verified.</li> <li><strong>Mold and process preparation:</strong> Mold surface, release agent and ambient conditions are checked.</li> <li><strong>Production and layup:</strong> Number of layers, orientation and resin ratio are monitored.</li> <li><strong>Dimensional measurement and tolerance:</strong> The part is compared against the drawing dimensions.</li> <li><strong>Visual and surface inspection:</strong> Cracks, voids, delamination and surface defects are sought.</li> <li><strong>Mechanical testing and validation:</strong> Strength tests are performed on samples when required.</li> </ol> <h2>Testing Methods</h2> <p>Both destructive and non-destructive testing methods are used for composites. Non-destructive testing (NDT) allows internal defects to be detected without damaging the part:</p> <table> <thead><tr><th>Method</th><th>Purpose</th><th>Type</th></tr></thead> <tbody> <tr><td>Visual inspection</td><td>Surface defects</td><td>Non-destructive</td></tr> <tr><td>Ultrasonic testing</td><td>Internal voids, delamination</td><td>Non-destructive</td></tr> <tr><td>Tensile/flexural test</td><td>Mechanical strength</td><td>Destructive</td></tr> <tr><td>Burn-off test</td><td>Fiber/resin ratio</td><td>Destructive</td></tr> </tbody> </table> <h2>Standards and Documentation</h2> <p>Quality control gains meaning through international standards and traceable documentation. Quality management systems such as ISO 9001 guarantee the repeatability of the process, while records kept for each batch make root-cause analysis possible in case of an issue. Traceability is the foundation of customer trust, especially in B2B and series-production projects.</p> <h2>Why Process Repeatability is Critical</h2> <p>Producing a single good part and producing thousands of parts at the same quality are different things. In composites, small deviations in process parameters (temperature, cure time, resin ratio) directly affect part performance. Therefore, fixing and continuously monitoring parameters during the transition to series production is one of the most critical topics.</p> <h2>Common Defects</h2> <p>The most common defects in composite manufacturing are resin-rich or resin-starved areas, air voids, delamination, incomplete cure and surface cracks. Most of these defects stem from deviations in process parameters or gaps in raw-material control. A defect detected at an early stage can be corrected at low cost, whereas a defect in a part already in the field is both costly and a reputational risk. For this reason, placing control points correctly along the production line is of great importance.</p> <h2>The Business Value of Quality Control</h2> <p>A well-designed quality-control process does not merely catch errors; it also reduces scrap rates, decreases customer returns and makes delivery times predictable. In B2B projects, consistent quality is the foundation of a long-term business relationship. Traceable records and compliance with standards put the customer''s trust in the supplier on a concrete footing. In short, quality control is not a cost item but an investment that creates a competitive advantage.</p> <h2>The Role of Digital Tools</h2> <p>Modern quality control does not rely solely on the human eye and manual measurement. Digital calipers, 3D scanners and data-collection systems ensure that measurements are recorded consistently and tracked on a batch basis. When the collected data is analyzed with statistical process control, a deviation can be noticed before it turns into a defect. This predictive approach significantly reduces the scrap rate, especially in high-volume production, and makes quality sustainable. As a result, digital quality control turns a reactive inspection task into a proactive engineering discipline that protects both the product and the customer relationship.</p> <p>MOE Kompozit designs its quality-control approach according to the part''s intended use and performance expectations, and runs the process with documentation from sample validation to series production.</p>'),
    'Explains why quality control in composite manufacturing is not just final inspection, covering the holistic process from raw material intake to testing and the critical points.',
    'Composite Quality Control Processes and Testing',
    'Quality control stages, testing methods, standards and a holistic approach to process repeatability in composite manufacturing for reliable parts.',
    'quality control, composite testing, ISO standards, NDT'
  ),
  (
    'bb020008-6008-4008-a008-bbbbbbbb0008',
    'bb010004-5004-4004-9004-bbbbbbbb0004',
    'en',
    'The Future of Industrial Composite Solutions',
    'industrial-composite-future',
    JSON_OBJECT('html', '<p>Composite materials are rapidly replacing traditional metals across many sectors. Thanks to their light weight, durability, corrosion resistance and design flexibility, their use in automotive, energy, construction and defense grows every year. Several key trends stand out that will accelerate this growth in the coming period.</p> <p>In this article we cover the technological and sector trends shaping the future of industrial composite solutions.</p> <h2>Trends Shaping the Future</h2> <p>The main topics setting the direction of composite technology in the coming years are:</p> <ul> <li><strong>Electric vehicle lightweighting:</strong> Structural parts that reduce vehicle weight to extend range.</li> <li><strong>Wind turbine blades:</strong> Longer, lighter and more efficient blade designs.</li> <li><strong>3D printed composites:</strong> Rapid prototyping and production for complex geometries.</li> <li><strong>Recyclable composites:</strong> Thermoplastic resins and a circular-economy approach.</li> <li><strong>Smart composites:</strong> Structures with embedded sensors that can monitor their own condition.</li> </ul> <h2>Sector Impact Table</h2> <table> <thead><tr><th>Sector</th><th>Expected Impact</th><th>Key Application</th></tr></thead> <tbody> <tr><td>Automotive</td><td>Lightweighting, range increase</td><td>Chassis and body parts</td></tr> <tr><td>Energy</td><td>Efficiency increase</td><td>Turbine blades</td></tr> <tr><td>Construction</td><td>Corrosion-free strength</td><td>Reinforcement profiles</td></tr> <tr><td>Defense</td><td>Strength-to-weight</td><td>Protective panels</td></tr> </tbody> </table> <h2>Sustainability and Recycling</h2> <p>One of the most important topics facing the composite sector is sustainability. While traditional thermoset resins create structures that are difficult to recycle, emerging thermoplastic composites and new recovery methods aim to extend the material''s life cycle. The circular-economy approach will become a decisive criterion in material selection in the future.</p> <h2>Digitalization in Manufacturing</h2> <p>Simulation, digital twin and automation technologies are making composite manufacturing more predictable and repeatable. Simulating the laminate design in advance reduces faulty production and shortens development time. These digital tools make it possible for even small manufacturers to reach high engineering quality.</p> <h2>Market Growth Dynamics</h2> <p>The global composite market is growing steadily due to pressure for lightweighting and energy efficiency. Emission targets in automotive, the shift to renewable sources in energy, and the need for durable infrastructure in construction are factors that directly increase composite demand. This growth is not limited to large manufacturers; mid-sized producers that work with the right engineering approach also capture significant opportunities in value-added niche applications.</p> <h2>Opportunities for Emerging Manufacturers</h2> <p>Thanks to a strong manufacturing base and favorable geography, regions like Turkey hold a competitive position in composite production. The development of local engineering capacity reduces dependence on imported products while increasing export potential. A wide range of applications, from amusement-park equipment to industrial enclosures, from agricultural equipment to municipal products, creates a sustainable growth area for local manufacturers. With the right material and process selection, these opportunities can be turned into concrete products that compete on both quality and price in international markets.</p> <h2>Innovations in Material Development</h2> <p>Advances in resin chemistry continuously expand the limits of composites. Faster-curing resins increase production speed, while bio-based resins reduce the environmental footprint. Structures that use carbon and glass fiber in hybrid form make it possible to strike new balances between cost and performance. Nano-additives, meanwhile, improve properties such as impact resistance and surface quality. These innovations make composites a genuine alternative in many applications where metal was previously mandatory.</p> <h2>Takeaways for Designers</h2> <p>Success in future composite projects depends on involving the material in the design at an early stage. When part geometry, load direction and production method are planned as a whole, the freedom that composites offer can be fully exploited. For this reason, early collaboration between engineering and production teams is the most effective approach to reducing both cost and development time. Investing in skilled engineers who understand laminate design, resin chemistry and production processes remains the single most decisive factor in unlocking the full potential of composite materials.</p> <p>MOE Kompozit follows these trends to offer its customers composite solutions suited not only to today''s needs but also to those of the future.</p>'),
    'A technical look at the future of industrial composite materials in light of trends such as electric vehicles, renewable energy, 3D printing and sustainability.',
    'The Future of Industrial Composite Solutions',
    'The future of composites: sector trends and innovation including electric vehicles, wind energy, 3D printing and recyclable composite materials.',
    'composite future, industrial composite, innovation, sustainability'
  )
